benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/customFields/{customFieldId}/auditLogsWithHistory - Retrieve custom field audit logs with history by id

covered: Valid Request: TC01 verifies successful retrieval (200) and checks Content-Type and that the body is an array of AuditLog objects.
Empty Response: TC02 and TC12 validate behavior when no audit logs exist (200 with empty JSON array).
Input Validation: TC05 checks invalid UUID format for customFieldId (400).
Non-existent resource handling: TC03 covers custom field not found (404).
Orphaned resource handling: TC04 covers associated Account missing (404).
Authentication/Authorization: TC06 and TC07 cover missing and invalid authentication tokens (401).
Error handling for backend failure: TC08 simulates database unavailability and expects 503.
Security: TC09 includes a SQL injection attempt and asserts no internal error leakage and safe response codes.
Edge cases & routing: TC10, TC15, TC16, TC17 cover extra path segments, missing path param, UUID boundary values, and leading/trailing spaces.
Performance & concurrency: TC11 and TC14 cover large result sets and concurrent request behavior and include response-time expectations.
Regression and backward compatibility: TC12 and TC13 check previously fixed behavior and older client User-Agent compatibility.
gaps: Pagination: No tests for pagination or limits (offset/limit/page) — how the API behaves for large result sets beyond a single full-array response is not verified.
Caching Behavior: No scenarios validate HTTP caching headers (ETag, Last-Modified, Cache-Control) or conditional GET (If-None-Match / 304 responses).
Rate Limiting / Throttling: No explicit tests for rate limiting (429) or server throttling under burst traffic — TC14 checks concurrency correctness/performance but not throttling behavior.
Schema-level validation: Tests assert "contains required fields" but there is no explicit test verifying field types, nullability, nested object schemas, or additional unexpected fields.
Authorization granularity: 403 Forbidden scenarios (valid auth but insufficient permissions) are not covered — only 401 is tested.
Internal server errors: No test that asserts handling/mapping of unexpected server-side errors to 500 (TC08 covers 503 but not generic 500).
Content negotiation / Accept header: No tests for Accept header handling (e.g., non-JSON accept or different media types).

Query parameters: The standard guideline mentions query parameters; the suite does not exercise any query param behavior (sorting/filtering), even if the endpoint might not support them — explicit tests would confirm rejection or support.
recommendations: Add pagination tests: if the API supports or will support pagination, add tests for offset/limit/page parameters, boundary pages, and behavior when requested page is beyond available data. Also test server behavior when returning very large arrays without pagination.

Add caching tests: verify ETag/Last-Modified/Cache-Control response headers, and conditional requests using If-None-Match / If-Modified-Since to assert 304 behavior and correctness of cache validation.
Add rate limiting/throttling tests: simulate burst requests to verify 429 responses and proper Retry-After header handling; differentiate from normal concurrency/performance tests.
Add strict schema validation tests: assert field names, types, required vs optional fields, formats (e.g., timestamps, UUIDs), and that no internal fields are leaked.
Add authorization-permission tests: include scenarios where authentication is valid but the caller lacks permission (expect 403) if RBAC/permission model applies.
Add generic server-error tests: simulate unexpected failures to confirm consistent 500 responses and that no stack traces or sensitive info are returned.
Add content negotiation tests: send differing Accept headers (e.g., application/xml, */*) and assert correct content-type negotiation and error handling.
If query parameters like filtering/sorting might be supported in future, add tests to confirm correct handling or explicit validation errors when unsupported.

Document which behaviors are out-of-scope for this endpoint (e.g., no pagination supported) so tests align with API contract; if the endpoint intentionally returns full arrays, add performance and memory-usage tests to validate production safety.
